When you invoke `fetch` multiple times the result order is not guaranteed to be the invocation one, due possible time within each asynchronous request.

There are various ways to go around this, and a simple one is to queue related operations, as example doing the 3rd point only once the 2nd happened.

This code is a basic example on how you could solve the issue, by creating a `fetch` wrapper that queue automatically each request.

Please note this is just a generic example to give you hints how you could queue multiple fetch requests.

    class FetchQueue {
      constructor() {
        this._queue = Promise.resolve();
      }
      fetch(
        args,   // used as fetch arguments, i.e. [&#39;page.php&#39;]
        before, // used on response headers, i.e. b =&gt; b.text()
        after   // used once fetch is finished
      ) {
        const $ = [].concat(args);
        this._queue = this._queue.then(
          () =&gt; fetch(...$).then(before).then(after)
        );
        return this;
      }
    }

    const fq = new FetchQueue;

    fq
      .fetch(&#39;/info.php&#39;, b =&gt; b.text(), console.log)
      // this will happen only after previous one has resolved
      .fetch(&#39;/post.php&#39;, b =&gt; b.json(), console.log)
    ;

You could basically use the `fq` wrapper to perform as many second points as you want, without any ability to cancel previous requests, as presented in this example, and then through the same instance post data.

Visually you don&#39;t need to block anything, the user will just need to eventually wait for previous changes to be notified, so that the submission will use any latest available data you have in your logic.

I hope this helps a little, at least understanding one way to queue asynchronous tasks without needing `async` and `await`, since the click on the submit button should be available regardless of the previous fetch operations.

